	<article id="post-843" class="post-843 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-uncategorized tag-advice tag-alignment tag-awareness tag-differences tag-relationships tag-understanding">
		<header class="entry-header">
						<h1 class="entry-title"><a href="http://facio.com/blog/2013/01/understand-the-annoyer-dont-dismiss-them/" title="Permalink to Understand the annoyer, don’t dismiss them" rel="bookmark">Understand the annoyer, don’t dismiss them</a></h1>
			
						<div class="entry-meta">
				<span class="sep">Posted on </span><a href="http://facio.com/blog/2013/01/understand-the-annoyer-dont-dismiss-them/" title="5:35 pm" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date" datetime="2013-01-15T17:35:24+00:00" pubdate>January 15, 2013</time></a><span class="by-author"> <span class="sep"> by </span> <span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="http://facio.com/blog/author/dirk/" title="View all posts by Dirk" rel="author">Dirk</a></span></span>			</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
			
<!--			--><!--			<div class="comments-link">-->
<!--				--><!--			</div>-->
<!--			-->		</header><!-- .entry-header -->

				<div class="entry-content">
			<figure class="alignleft" style="width: 300px;"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-488" title="Understand the Annoyer" src="http://facio.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/UnderstandTheAnnoyer-e1359499277150.jpg" alt="Phone" /></p>
<figcaption>We may not get along, but that doesn&#8217;t mean the other person is broken.</figcaption>
</figure>
<p>Most of us assign moral failing to others who are different than us. The networker who flits their way around the social event is “superficial”. The quiet person who stays in the corner and doesn’t have much to say is “boring”. The loud person performing for a group not sensitive to the noise and space needs of people around them is “obnoxious”. The intellectual who has a critical word for seemingly everything is “arrogant”.</p>
<p>Diminishing others with such language and framing is a huge mistake that we almost universally make. We attribute to their <em>character</em> what are actually facets of their <em>inherent personality</em>. Sure, it is much easier to translate the discomfort they make us feel into some failing on their part. However, most of the time, it is not a failing by either party and instead an incompatibility between them. Indeed, each of us know other people who we “can’t stand”, yet sure enough they have friends, family, people who like and trust them. The problem isn’t them, it is the intersection between who we are, and who they are.</p>
<p>This stretches beyond personality as well. Sometimes the issue is one of territory. There can only be one CEO, so people who otherwise would get along begin seeing one another negatively because their ambitions are contradictory. Other times the issue is one of time: I am in a hurry and the other person is not. This creates conflict as we try to accomplish different things in different ways. Most of the time, in all of these cases, we turn that friction between us into a judgement of the other person. We objectify and diminish them, rather than saving blame and viewing the situation more objectively. After all, when someone blocks us or makes us feel uncomfortable, it is easier and more cathartic to say “What an a-hole!” instead of, “Ah, he’s just an extraverted intuitive.”</p>
<p>To improve your mental health and capacity for bringing goodness to the world, be aware of these judgement that you make as you go thru life. Turn the aspersions toward the other person into a recognition that you just aren’t lining up with each other. That might make you uncomfortable, but it surely does not make them bad.</p>
					</div><!-- .entry-content -->
		
        <div class="entry-footer">

