	<article id="post-353" class="post-353 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-myers-briggs tag-myers-briggs tag-understanding">
		<header class="entry-header">
						<h1 class="entry-title"><a href="http://facio.com/blog/2012/07/friction-and-your-myers-briggs-type/" title="Permalink to Friction and your Myers-Briggs type" rel="bookmark">Friction and your Myers-Briggs type</a></h1>
			
						<div class="entry-meta">
				<span class="sep">Posted on </span><a href="http://facio.com/blog/2012/07/friction-and-your-myers-briggs-type/" title="12:00 pm" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date" datetime="2012-07-24T12:00:05+00:00" pubdate>July 24, 2012</time></a><span class="by-author"> <span class="sep"> by </span> <span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="http://facio.com/blog/author/dirk/" title="View all posts by Dirk" rel="author">Dirk</a></span></span>			</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
			
<!--			--><!--			<div class="comments-link">-->
<!--				--><!--			</div>-->
<!--			-->		</header><!-- .entry-header -->

				<div class="entry-content">
			<p>As I&#8217;ve become increasingly well-versed in the Myers-Briggs Type Indicator(R) over the past couple of years, I keep discovering it is like an onion: the deeper you get the more layers there are. The big downside with the MBTI and the general Myers-Briggs style preference frameworks is the relative complexity. The presentation of one&#8217;s type in 16 categories using obtuse letters can be arcane for many users. The upside is, for serious analysis and study, it is much deeper than the preponderance of other tools out there. That&#8217;s why there are so many layers to keep exploring.</p>
<p>In studying my own type and behaviour, I intuitively felt there were inherent frictions between my facets, frictions that I suspected were not unique to me but common to many people of particular types. Talking about this over dinner with my friend Ann, an MBTI Master Practitioner, she acknowledged that what I was intuiting was a very real part of type dynamics. This is useful enough to provide interesting personal insights that I want to share it here.</p>
<p>For the purpose of this analysis, we are looking at how one&#8217;s Attitudes (E-I) relate to their Judging Functions (T-F) and how one&#8217;s Perceiving Functions (S-N) relate to their Lifestyle (J-P). Half of these pairing represent what I will call a &#8220;natural alignment&#8221; that lend themselves to a more comfortable natural functioning and the other half represent what I will call a &#8220;natural conflict&#8221;, providing friction for a person going through their life. Those labels are just convenient for this short post and are not suggested as formal labels to identify these characteristics beyond this.</p>
<table style="margin: 0px 20px 20px 0; float: left; border: 1px solid #303030; padding: 20px;">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td style="font-size: 20px;" colspan="4">Naturally Aligned Pairs</td>
</tr>
<tr style="font-size: 32px; font-weight: bold;">
<td class="mbti-type-pair">E-F</td>
<td class="mbti-type-pair">I-T</td>
<td class="mbti-type-pair">S-J</td>
<td class="mbti-type-pair">N-P</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>E-F (Extraversion-Feeling) &#8211; getting your energy from other people, and making first judgements in people-centered ways</p>
<p>I-T (Introversion-Thinking) &#8211; getting your energy from inside yourself, and making first judgements in objective ways</p>
<p>S-J (Sensing-Judging) &#8211; perceiving the world in the moment through your senses, and making in-the-moment decisions and moving on to the next thing</p>
<p>N-P (iNtuition-Perceiving) &#8211; perceiving the world of ideas through your mind, and being compelled to delay decisions to keep options open</p>
<p>Those come together so naturally it may not be immediately apparent those short explanations are summarizing BOTH of the pairs they represent. The good news for those with strong alignment is they likely fit into the expectations of others better, and suffer less internal friction thanks to not naturally being compelled toward divergent ways of functioning. Now, look at the next list:</p>
<table style="margin: 0 20px 20px 0; float: left; border: 1px solid #303030; padding: 20px;">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td style="font-size: 20px;" colspan="4">Naturally Conflicting Pairs</td>
</tr>
<tr style="font-size: 32px; font-weight: bold;">
<td class="mbti-type-pair">E-T</td>
<td class="mbti-type-pair">I-F</td>
<td class="mbti-type-pair">S-P</td>
<td class="mbti-type-pair">N-J</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>E-T (Extraversion-Thinking) &#8211; getting your energy from other people, and making first judgments in objective ways</p>
<p>I-F (Introversion-Feeling) &#8211; getting your energy from inside yourself, and making first judgements in people-centered ways</p>
<p>S-P (Sensing-Perceiving) &#8211; perceiving the world in the moment through your senses, and being compelled to delay decisions to keep options open</p>
<p>N-J (iNtuition-Judging) &#8211; perceiving the world of ideas through your mind, and making in-the-moment decisions to close off one thing and move on to the next</p>
<p>See the contrast?</p>
<p>When your inherent preferences are thus conflicting, it is reflected in how others perceive you and how you manage yourself. For example, someone who is an E-T will seem friendly and gregarious, then will surprise you with their harsh criticism. Whereas, if an I -T were to criticize harshly you would be more likely to expect it based on other behavioural cues and natural assumptions. Or, an I-F is likely struggling inside of themselves, on one hand wanting their solitary time in order to be nurtured and replenished, while wanting to care for and deeply engage with someone else. The path forward is not simple, and gratifying either necessarily rubs the other one the wrong way. For people whose type has both pairs conflicting &#8211; ESTP, ENTJ, ISFP, INFJ &#8211; life and identity can seem particularly draining. Of course, on the flip side successful CEO&#8217;s are disproportionately ENTJs, and great artists are disproportionately ISFP&#8217;s. So while there may be a price to pay for that conflict, there are also successes and achievement borne from the trials of contradiction.</p>
<p>Of course, let us not forget that who and what we are is the product of many vectors, beyond our Myers-Briggs style preferences. So the impact of strong alignment or mis-alignment for each person can be significantly different. However, awareness of these dynamics can put us in better touch with ourselves, help us understand what is going on as we function and make decisions, and perhaps even better understand each other.</p>
					</div><!-- .entry-content -->
		
        <div class="entry-footer">

